      <example>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <ol>
              <li>
                Make a truth table for <m>p \to (\neg q \vee r)</m>
              </li>
              <li>
                Construct the truth table for the compound statement <m>(p \to q) \wedge (\neg p \to q)</m>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>

        </statement>
      </example>

      <p>
        Occassionally through this course, we will be working with bit objects. A <term>bit</term> is a number which has values of either 1 or 0. We can operate with bits the same way we operate with propositions: 0 is false and 1 is true. The truth tables for the operations <m>\vee, \wedge, \oplus</m> all apply.
      </p>
      <example>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find the bitwise OR, AND, and XOR of the pair of bitstrings:
            <ul>
              <li>0101 1010</li>
              <li>1011 0110</li>
            </ul>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            <ul>
              <li>  OR: 1111 1110</li>
              <li>  AND: 0001 0010</li>
              <li>  XOR: 1110 1100</li>
            </ul>
          </p>
        </answer>
      </example>
