  <section xml:id="section-prop-apps">
    <title>Applications of Propositional Logic</title>

    <subsection>
      <title> Translating English Sentences</title>

      <example>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Decompose each part of the statement into individual propositional variables and write as a compound proposition:
            <ol>
              <li> You drink coffee only if you put the ground coffee into the maker and don't forget to press brew. </li>
              <li> TODO </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p> Answering the coffee question, we let: 
          <ul>
            <li><m>d</m>: You can drink coffee.</li>
            <li><m>g</m>: You put ground coffee into the maker</li>
            <li><m>f</m>: You forgot to press brew.</li>
          </ul>
          Then the statement is <m>d \to (g \wedge \neg f)</m>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </example>

    </subsection>
    <subsection>
      <title>Boolean Searches</title>
      <p>
        Search engines using Boolean searches use logical connectives. 
        <ul>
          <li> AND requires records match both terms </li>
          <li> OR returns records that match one or both of the terms </li>
          <li> NOT (or sometimes AND NOT) excludes a term </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
      <p>
        For example, if I wanted to search the WSU library catalog to learn about Georg Cantor's diagonalization argument <xref ref="section-objects-sets-diag"/>, but I want to exclude anything about computability, I could do the following search: 
        <image source="images/library-catalog.png"/>

        <note>
          <p>
            Remember that <q>but</q> is a conjunction!
          </p>
        </note>

      </p>
    </subsection>
    <subsection>
      <title>Logic Puzzles</title>
      <p>
        A classic example is that we're on the island of knights and knaves. Knights always tell the truth. Knaves always lie.
      </p>
      <example>
        <statement>
          <p>
            We encounter two people A and B.
            <ul>
              <li>
                A says: <q>B is a knight.</q>
              </li>
              <li>
                B says: <q>The two of us are opposite types.</q>
              </li>
            </ul>
            What is the conclusion?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </example>
    </subsection>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="section-logic-equivalences">
    <title>Logical Equivalences</title>

    <definition>
      <p>
        An expression involving logical variables that is true for all values is called a <term>tautology</term>.
      </p>
    </definition>

    <definition>
      <p>
        An expression involving logical variables that is false for all values is called a <term>contradiction</term>.
      </p>
    </definition>

    <p>
      Statements that are not tautologies or contradictions are called <term>contingencies</term>. Tautologies and contradictions are special, so they get special defined names.
    </p>

    <definition>
      <p>
        We say two propositions <m>p</m> and <m>q</m> are <term>logically equivalent</term> if <m>p \leftrightarrow q</m> is a tautology. We denote this by <m>p \equiv q</m>.
      </p>
    </definition>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Prove the following are equivalent using a truth table.
          <ol>
            <li> <m>p \vee (p \wedge q) \equiv p </m></li>
            <li> <m>p \vee (q \wedge r) \equiv (p \vee q) \wedge (p \vee r)</m>
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>p \to q \equiv \neg p \vee q</m> 
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
        <p>
          <note>
            <p>
              We use <m>p \to q \equiv \neg p \vee q</m> often enough that this has a name. Those from WSU's intro to logic class call it <term>implication</term>
            </p>
          </note>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <p>
      The following is a collection of very useful tautologies. Do you need to memorize them? Absolutely!
    </p>
    <table xml:id="table-equivalences">
      <!-- table modified from https://github.com/klevasseur/ads //-->
      <caption>Basic Logical Laws - Equivalences</caption>
      <tabular  halign="center">
        <row>	
          <cell></cell>
          <cell>Commutative Laws</cell>
          <cell></cell>
        </row>
        <row bottom="medium">
          <cell> <m>p \lor  q\equiv q\lor p</m>  </cell>
          <cell></cell>
          <cell> <m>p \land q\equiv q \land p</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell></cell>
          <cell>Associative Laws</cell>
          <cell></cell>
        </row>
        <row bottom="medium">
          <cell><m>(p \lor  q) \lor r \equiv  p \lor  (q \lor  r)</m></cell>
          <cell></cell>
          <cell>(<m>p \land q) \land r\equiv p \land  (q \land  r)</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell></cell>
          <cell>Distributive Laws</cell>
          <cell></cell>
        </row>
        <row bottom="medium">
          <cell><m>p \land  (q \lor  r) \equiv  (p \land  q ) \lor  (p \land  r)</m></cell>
          <cell></cell>
          <cell><m>p \lor  (q \land  r) \equiv  (p \lor  q) \land (p \lor r)</m> </cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell></cell>
          <cell>Identity Laws</cell>
          <cell></cell>
        </row>
        <row bottom="medium">
          <cell><m>p \lor  F\equiv p</m></cell>
          <cell></cell>
          <cell> <m>p \land  T \equiv p</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell></cell>
          <cell>Negation Laws</cell>
          <cell></cell>
        </row>
        <row bottom="medium">
          <cell><m>p\land \neg p\equiv F</m></cell>
          <cell></cell>
          <cell> <m>p\lor \neg p\equiv T</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell></cell>
          <cell>Idempotent Laws</cell>
          <cell></cell>
        </row>
        <row bottom="medium">
          <cell><m>p \lor  p \equiv p</m> </cell>
          <cell></cell>
          <cell>  <m>p\land p \equiv p</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell></cell>
          <cell>Domination Laws</cell>
          <cell></cell>
        </row>
        <row bottom="medium">
          <cell><m>p \land F \equiv F</m> </cell>
          <cell></cell>
          <cell> <m>p \lor  T \equiv T</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell></cell>
          <cell>Absorption Laws</cell>
          <cell></cell>
        </row>
        <row bottom="medium">
          <cell><m>p \land (p\lor  q)\equiv p</m></cell>
          <cell></cell>
          <cell><m>p \lor  (p \land  q) \equiv  p</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell></cell>
          <cell>DeMorgan's Laws</cell>
          <cell></cell>
        </row>
        <row bottom="medium">
          <cell><m>\neg (p \lor  q) \equiv  (\neg p) \land  (\neg q)</m></cell>
          <cell></cell>
          <cell><m>\neg (p \land  q) \equiv  (\neg p) \lor  (\neg q)</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell></cell>
          <cell>Double Negation Law</cell>
          <cell></cell>
        </row>
        <row bottom="medium">
          <cell></cell>
          <cell> <m>\neg (\neg p)\equiv p</m></cell>
          <cell></cell>
        </row>
      </tabular>
    </table>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Use existing logical equivalences from <xref ref="table-equivalences"/> to show the following are equivalent.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <m>p \wedge q \equiv \neg(p \to \neg q)</m>
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>(p \to r) \vee (q \to r)</m> and <m>(p \wedge q) \to r</m> 
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>q \to p \equiv \neg p \to \neg q</m>
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>\neg(p \to q) \equiv  p \wedge \neg q</m>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
        <p><note>
          <p>
            This is your first experience with logical proof! It won't be your last. Much of this class is about learning to understand and argue rigorously.
          </p>
        </note>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="section-logic-quantifiers">
    <title>Predicates and Logical Quantifiers</title>
    <subsection>
      <title>Predicates</title>
      <p>
        Consider this mathematical sentence: <q> <m> x \lt 5 </m></q>.
        <ul>
          <li><m>x</m> is a variable, the subject of the sentence.</li>
          <li> <q>is less than five</q> is the <term> predicate</term></li>
          <ul>
            <li> A predicate is a property that a subject can have.</li>
          </ul>
          <li> <m>P(x) :=</m> <q><m> x \lt 5 </m></q>
          <ul>
            <li> The value of <m>P(x)</m> is the value of the <term>propositional function</term> P at <m>x</m>. </li>
            <li>Assigning a value to <m>x</m> makes <m>P</m> a proposition (it then has a truth value)</li>
          </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>

      <definition>
        <p>
          The <term>domain of discourse</term> (or <term>universe of discourse</term>) is the collection from which variables can take values.
        </p>
        <p> For example, if my predicate function is <q><m>x</m> is a student at WSU</q>, the function has a different meaning if my universe of discourse is <q>all college students</q> versus <q>all powers of 5</q>
        </p>
      </definition>

      <example>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Determine the truth values of the following:
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Let <m>P(x)</m> be the statement <q>The word <m>x </m> contains the letter a</q>.
                  <ol>
                    <li> P(elephant)</li>
                    <li>
                      P(purple)
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      P(true)
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      P(false)
                    </li>
                  </ol>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Let <m>Q(x,y)</m> be the statement <q><m>x^2 + y^2 = 25</m></q>.
                  <ol>
                    <li><m>Q(4,5)</m></li>
                    <li><m>Q(3,4)</m></li>
                  </ol>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </example>
    </subsection>

    <subsection>
      <title>Logical Quantifiers</title>

      <definition>
        <p>
          The <term>universal quantification</term> of <m>P(x)</m> is the statement that <m>P(x)</m> is true for all values of <m>x</m> in the domain of discourse. We write <m> \forall x P(x)</m>
        </p>
        <p>
          An <m>x</m> value for which <m>P(x)</m> is false is called a <term>counterexample</term>
        </p>
      </definition>
      <definition>
        <p>
          The <term>existential quantification</term> of <m>P(x)</m> is the statement that there is some value <m>x</m> in the universe of discourse for which <m>P(x)</m> is true. We write <m> \exists x P(x)</m>
        </p>
      </definition>


      <example>
        <statement>
          Let <m>P(x)</m> be <q><m>x^2 \ge 0</m></q>. What is the truth value of <m>\forall x P(x)</m> if the domain is:
          <ol>
            <li> All real numbers </li>
            <li> All complex numbers </li>
          </ol>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <ol>
            <li> Since <m>x^2 \ge 0</m> for all real numbers (what you learned in Algebra is true), this statement is true.</li>
            <li> This is false. Let <m> x = \sqrt{-1}</m>. Then <m>(\sqrt{-1})^2 = -1 \not\ge 0</m>.</li>
          </ol>
          <p>
            We showed that <m>\sqrt{-1}</m> is a counterexample to the universal quanfication.
          </p>
        </answer>
      </example>

      <example>
        <statement>
          <p> We can combine quantifers, where each variable might come from a different domain. Precedence of quantifiers is left to right.
          </p>
          <p>
